The area

Neighborhood: Poblenou
The futuristic Agbar Tower stands out from Barcelona's skyline in Poblenou. It is no coincidence then that this area of town is the newly crowned technological park of the city, its own mini Silicon Valley containing a tech incubator (Barcelona Activa) as well as a host of local and international high tech companies. To accommodate the onrush of new residents and workers, the area of Poblenou has seen a surge of activity in new high-rise residential buildings and two top-notch shopping centers catering to everyone's need. The ambiance of this area is calmer than the city center and the beautifully relaxing Bogatell Beach, popular with locals, is just a handful of blocks away.

  • Poblenou • 6 min walk

Very Local District
Aug 2024 • Couples
Not just the Rambla street but Poblenou district as a whole is great.
Loads of typical local Spanish shops, bars and restaurants.
Don’t think we saw one shop selling touristy stuff. ( could be wrong )
A residential area with schools, flats, a church so different from the centre of the city.
Lots of narrow streets many with attractive buildings.
The Poblenou Rambla comes alive at night, many shops open late, lots of restaurants & plenty of seating areas along the way.
We stayed in the Melia hotel and enjoyed quiet evenings in the area away from the City.
Written September 8, 2024

Houston, TX74 contributions
Family spot not faraway from the city, yet relaxed and accessible
Jun 2024 • Family
The Rambla offers the family atmosphere of a small town with all the accessibility and benefits of a big city. Great walk with the family after a great meal and dessert from local providers and restaurants. There are supermarkets, pharmacies and plenty of restaurants/bars.

Plenty of variety and options. The beach is about a 6-10 minute walk, there are hotels, hostels and plenty of airbnb options around. Transportation is accessible, from public to private. Parking might be a difficulty in the street specially if you are not local to traffic rules.

As a family, this is a great place to chose for a short or long stay, 15 minutes from Barcelona and 6-10 minute walk from the beach.
Written June 24, 2024

Far from the madding crowd
Jul 2023 • Couples
Great place to visit for food and drink. Tables are situated along the centre of the road. There are hardly any cars so it is a safe walk for pedestrians.
This road is much nicer than La Rambla in the centre of town with less tourists and more locals.
Nearest metro is Poblenou on line 4.
We had lunch and dinner at restaurants along this rambla and they were superb.
The rambla leads down to the beach, one of which is Platja de la Mar Bella which is a clothing optional beach.
Written August 3, 2023

Great thoroughfare
Feb 2023 • Couples
At the heart of this vibrant district, the Rambla stretches for almost 2 kilometers. To the eponymous Parc. And just beyond to the sea.

It’s a grand stroll, pedestrianised in parts. Retail, cafes and restaurants abound. About half ways along is the great monument to Doctor Trueta.

He was a local born polymath. Over a lifetime of achievement he had a lengthy tenure as Professor of Orthopaedic Surgery at Oxford University.

File under: Hidden Gem
Oct 2022
Smaller and more intimate than the famous 'La Rambla', this is a much more enjoyable street. Lots of little shops and bars to eat drink and (window-)shop.
Our favourite was Bar Nuria at #34 that I can't find here on Tripadvisor. The bacalau croquetas are to die for!
When travelling north-west, when you get to Carrer del Perú go one block south-west, then continue on Carrer de la Llacuna and Carrer de Rogent for another lovely pedestrianised shopping street.
